observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LCE instruct the MA to:
a. prepare the necessary Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) to adjust/reverse the improper/improper/erroneous entries;
b. undertake a one-time cleansing of the Due to LGUs and Due to NGAs accounts by following the guidelines and procedures for the write-off of dormant accounts, reconciling the balances of the accounts;
c. maintain SL for the Due to LGUs and Due to NGAs accounts under General Fund (GF) and immediately present the same to the Office of the Auditor for verification and review;
d. regularly update the SL to ensure accurate tracking of transactions; and
e. strictly comply with the stipulations stated in the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) and avoid delay in the implementation of the project.

We recommended that Management instruct the:
a. Municipal Accountant (MA) to
(i) maintain Supplies Ledger Card (SLC) for each commodity/stock;
(ii) record all procurement of inventory supplies in the books of accounts using the Perpetual Inventory System;
(iii) draw the necessary Journal entries to derecognize the amount of Welfare Goods Supplies amounting to ₱2,480,000.00;
(iv) draw the necessary journal entries to adjust the correct amount of Drugs and Medicines Inventory, Medical, Dental and Laboratory Supplies, Office Supplies and Other Office Supplies and Materials Inventory as at year-end amounting to ₱1,596,240.50, ₱1,514,114.00, ₱228,404.00 and ₱40.00, respectively; and
(v) be more vigilant to ensure that issued supplies and materials were recorded to appropriate expense accounts; and
b. General Services Officer (GSO) to
(i) maintain stock cards for each item of inventory;
(ii) regularly reconcile the stock cards with the SLCs of the Municipal Accounting Office (MAO);
(iii) report the issuances of supplies thru the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) supported with Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) and/or proof of distribution of goods and supplies and furnish a copy thereof to the MA which shall be the basis in recording to appropriate Expenses accounts; and
(iv) submit the physical count of stocks of all supplies and materials reports to the Office of the Auditor and other offices concerned on a semi-annual basis.

We recommended the LCE to:

require the SB Members, Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer to provide a written justification on the (i) non-uniformity of COVID-19 HP received by the employees; (ii) failure to enact a resolution authorizing and adopting the guidelines on the grant thereof; and (iii) charging of COVID-19 HP of permanent employees to MOOE rather than PS;

require the concerned employees to refund the amount of ₱7,900.00 representing their claims on March 16, 2020;

require the job order employed by the Provincial Government to refund the amount of ₱27,000.00 representing claims for the period April 1, 2020 to December 31, 2020;

provide legal basis for the granting of COVID-19 HP for the period May 16 to December 31, 2020;

advise the Human Resource Management Office to submit, if any, the required (i) order authorizing the employees to physically report for work; and (ii) copy of the duties and responsibilities of contract of service and job order personnel during the period of grant; and

instruct the Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking documents in Appendix B as well as the DVs and SDs such as DTRs to provide basis for the computation of actual days worked and Accomplishment Reports of the aforementioned employees for the period June 1 to December 31, 2020.

We recommended the LCE to direct the Municipal Accountant and BAC 

submit the required documents to the Office of the Auditor for further evaluation of the transactions;

comply with the posting requirements for information purposes and transparency; 


ensure that all the SDs are properly signed and provided with complete information; and


submit a written explanation on the acceptance of OSS which are notarized after the payment.

We further recommended that the LCE instruct the concerned offices to stop the practice of payment thru reimbursement basis.

We recommended that management:

strictly enforce the “No Segregation, No Collection Policy” scheme of the Municipality;


ensure that waste collectors and segregators are equipped with personal protective equipment to free them from hazards of handling solid wastes;


consider the purchase of vehicle specifically designed for the collection, transport and disposal of solid wastes by providing adequate budget thereon; and

intensify the information and education campaign to stop totally the open burning of solid wastes in the different barangays and impose penalty to violators.

We recommended that management:
strictly enforce the “No Segregation, No Collection Policy” scheme of the Municipality;
ensure that waste collectors and segregators are equipped with personal protective equipment to free them from hazards of handling solid wastes;
consider the purchase of vehicle specifically designed for the collection, transport and disposal of solid wastes by providing adequate budget thereon; and
intensify the information and education campaign to stop totally the open burning of solid wastes in the different barangays and impose penalty to violators.

We recommended that management:

centralize the hiring of job order, contractual and honoraria-based personnel at the HRMO to ensure the completeness and reliability of records;

reduce the number of job order/contractual personnel to the bare essential based on actual project/program needs;


instruct the Personnel Officer to require job order personnel to submit verified/certified accomplishment reports to support the propriety of the payment of their wages; and maintain an updated and complete records (201 files) for the job order, contractual and honoraria-based personnel for reference purposes; and

direct the Personnel Officer and Heads of Offices concerned to submit their explanation for (i) allowing payment of wages out of Municipal fund of those personnel who render services to Camp Kainomayan, a private company and the driver of private vehicles transporting to Mt. Pinatubo and Tukal-Tukal Falls; and (ii) absence of action against 279 personnel who failed to appear during the head count conducted by the Audit Team.

We recommended that management: 

(a) consider the DENR survey on high risk areas in setting priorities in the implementation of projects to ensure reduction of disaster risk and enhancement of disaster preparedness; 

(b) provide livelihood/relief assistance to disaster victims instead of cash in accordance with Section 5.3 of NDRRMC, DBM and DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1; 


(c)  instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to review the disbursements and items of expenditures for propriety of charging to LDRRMF before certifying the existence of appropriation; and 

(d) require the Municipal Agriculturist to submit thru the Municipal Accountant photographs of the damage to support his validation on the typhoon affected area.

We recommended that management:

(a) comply fully with the provision of protective gears and supplies to garbage sorters and collectors; 

(b) intensity information drive on proper waste segregation by providing properly labeled trash cans, signages and billboards; 


(c) monitor closely the SWM personnel assigned at the Municipal MRF in Barangay Panan to ensure proper waste disposal; 

(d) find an appropriate location as containment area for the residual wastes to prevent harmful effects to human beings and environment; 

(e) compel all barangays to enforce the Municipal SWM and to participate actively in all programs, projects and activities of the Municipality for the successful implementation of the 10-year SWM plan, particularly the proper segregation at source and disposal of wastes at the designated MRF; and 


(f) impose garbage fees for the collection of wastes of all institutions, establishments, and households to generate additional funds for the implementation of SWM, and enforce charging of fines and penalties to violators of prohibited acts as a deterrent mechanism.

We reiterated our audit recommendations that management:

require the participation and cooperation of all offices and the Committee on Inventory, thru issuance of an Office Memorandum, in the completion of the physical count of the Municipality’s property, plant and equipment, including land, books, equipment, furniture and fixtures, work animals, and other property, plant and equipment recorded under the General Fund and Special Education Fund; conduct physical inventory of all infrastructure assets, buildings, and other structures; and complete the report on unserviceable properties to provide basis for the reconciliation of the records of the GSO with those of the Accounting Office;
create an investigation team, disposal committee and appraisal committee to resolve issues such as PPE variances, inexistence of properties, inaction on unserviceable properties and absence of valuation for donated assets, respectively;
confer with the donors of motor vehicles to provide all documents related thereto, including the deed of donation to have full ownership of the properties; and
instruct the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to exert effort to locate/trace the documents of previous years to serve as reference of the investigating body in case of unlocated properties and in the adjustment of the unreconciled accounts; prepare an ARE renewal at least every three years for each accountable officer as proof of receipt of the properties.

We recommended that the management and the Municipal Accountant:

exhaust all possible remedies for the collection of the livelihood loans;
issue Demand Letters to all debtors without exemption;
communicate and meet personally with the debtors to determine the possibility of collection and the need to provide allowance for impairment.  In case the requirements were not met, the Municipal Accountant may request write-off of the long outstanding and non-existing livelihood loans;
send confirmation to the DBM regarding the availability of funds for the MRF project and the overpayment of supplies; and
in case of the erroneous recording of unreleased funds from the DBM, prepare an adjustment to state correctly the balance of the Receivables account.

We recommended that the management:

assist the officials of Kainomayan Goat Raiser Association of Botolan in the procurement of 80 goats for immediate release/distribution to beneficiaries;
require the supplier to refund the cost of 14 dead goats for inferior quality or charge concerned officials for negligence of duties at the time of delivery/inspection/acceptance of goats;
oblige the LPRAT to undertake periodic monitoring of the project and members’ compliance to the project proposal;
require the Municipal Accountant to record the transfer of funds as Receivable to NGOs and oblige the officials of the Associations for the proper liquidation of the fund transfer; and
for future projects, develop a clear-cut policy regarding the system/procedures to be followed by the beneficiaries or enter into a Memorandum of Agreement with them to achieve a more sustainable livelihood program.

We recommended that the management:

obtain the assistance of the Committee on Award, the Market Administrator, and the Collector in the proper enforcement of the existing policies on the rental of market stalls;

ensure that all pertinent data and records are intact as basis for the determination of market fees due;

legalize the rental agreement thru issuance of duly approved Application for Lease to all stallholders;

maintain a complete and updated registry book containing vital information about the stallholder; i.e. names and address, number and description of stalls occupied, location, date and time of receipt of application, and contract period;

review the existing contracts and re-examine the applicability of rates imposed based on actual stall size and site;

collect fees from stallholder/s occupying space intended for business and require to use the provided storeroom;

impose surcharges against delinquent stallholders to encourage prompt settlement of accounts and defer possible cancellation of their contracts unless with approved condonation and for valid reasons;

consider the revision of the policies concerning the rates for the Main Building – first floor (isle), second floor, Annex A and big commercial establishments, and define the coverage of the first to fourth layer of the stalls.  Strict implementation of the provisions would benefit the Municipality from an increased collection of rental from market stalls.

We reiterated our audit recommendations that management:
a)	require the participation and cooperation of all offices and the Committee on Inventory, thru issuance of an Office Memorandum, in the completion of the physical count of the Municipality’s property, plant and equipment, including land, books, equipment, furniture and fixtures, work animals, and other property, plant and equipment recorded under the General Fund and Special Education Fund; conduct physical inventory of all infrastructure assets, buildings, and other structures; and complete the report on unserviceable properties to provide basis for the reconciliation of the records of the GSO with those of the Accounting Office;
b)  	create an investigation team, disposal committee, and appraisal committee to resolve issues, such as PPE variances, inexistence of properties, inaction on unserviceable properties, and absence of valuation for donated assets, respectively;
c)	confer with the donors of motor vehicles to provide all documents related thereto, including the deed of donation to acquire absolute ownership of the properties; and
d)	instruct the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to exert effort to locate/trace the documents of previous years to serve as reference of the investigating body in case of unlocated properties and in the adjustment of the unreconciled accounts; and prepare an ARE renewable at least every three years for each accountable officer as proof of receipt of the properties.

We recommended that management:

instruct the Committee on Inventory to update the inventory report for equipment and furniture and fixtures including land, books, animals and other property, plant and equipment; pursue the physical inventory of infrastructure assets, buildings and other structures; and prepare separate report for the unserviceable properties in order to provide basis for reconciliation on the record of the GSO and Accounting Office;
create an investigation team, disposal committee and appraisal committee to resolve issues such as PPE variances, inexistence of properties, inaction on unserviceable properties and absence of valuation for donated assets, respectively;





confer with the donors of motor vehicles to provide all documents related thereto, including the deed of donation to have full ownership of the properties; and
instruct the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to exert effort to locate documents of previous years for reference by the investigating body in case of properties that could not be located and basis for the adjustment of the unreconciled accounts; prepare an ARE for each accountable officer as proof of receipt of the properties; and provide depreciation for the Buildings, Disaster Response, and Rescue Equipment and Books accounts based on the prescribed estimated useful lives of the assets.

We recommended that management:

conduct intensive planning and constant monitoring of projects to preclude recurrence of unutilized funds;
efficiently and effectively execute the projects as planned to obtain maximum benefits therefrom;
revisit the 20% Development Plan and align PPAs along the perspective of the JMC of the DILG/DBM in order to ensure quality project outcomes that promise long-term benefits to the constituents;
require all or majority of BAC members to decide/certify/sign the Abstracts of Quotation, in case of procurement thru shopping and other alternative modes; and

oblige all bidders to include in their omnibus sworn statements a complete testimony to prove their integrity as contractors/suppliers in accordance with the requirements of Section 25.3 of the 2016 Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations of R.A. No. 9184.

We recommended that management:

give priority and enforce the implementation of the existing Ordinance on the Municipal Solid Waste Management for the attainment of the commitment of the LGU towards environmental protection and effective solid waste management;
compel all barangays to enforce the Municipal SWM and actively participate in all programs, projects and activities of the Municipality for the successful implementation of the ten-year SWM plan and ensure proper segregation and disposal of wastes;
settle down with the Director of DOST the problems encountered in the operation of the machines and comply with the respective obligations stipulated in the MOA inasmuch as the machines are almost paid;
appropriate sufficient funds for the purchase of dump truck to solve the problem on the collection of residual wastes to other Barangays, materials for the operation of machines, and lacking equipment of SWM personnel;
issue memorandum to all SWM personnel giving instructions on their daily target of performing duties and responsibilities such as collection, segregation and disposal of wastes, and operation of the machine to resolve voluminous wastes coming into the MRF, and require garbage personnel on the constant wearing of protective equipment for their own safety;  
find an appropriate location as containment area for the residual wastes to prevent harmful effects to human beings and environment;


provide cover on garbage truck to prevent scattering of wastes and spreading of awful odor, and imprint telephone number on the body of the dump truck in case of notification for immediate pick-up of wastes; provide labels on trash bins to inform users about segregation of wastes; and signage’s in areas to make constituents aware of the strict implementation of the SWM; 
impose garbage fees to all institutions, establishments, and households for the collection of wastes to generate additional funds for the implementation of SWM, and fines and penalties to violators of the prohibited acts to enforce the Municipal SWM; and
require the Sanggunian to revisit the Ordinance to amend the provision that was inadvertently omitted particularly the prescribed period and frequency of collection of garbage fees under Section 1 of Article VIII, as well as the fines and penalties enforceable against prohibited acts under paragraphs 2 and 3 of Section 2, Article IX thereof.

We recommended that management:

strictly enforce the existing rules and regulations in the operation of all motor vehicles including tricycles in the Municipality;
instruct the Municipal Treasurer to impose correct permit fees in accordance with the Revenue Code.  Scrutinize the requirements and have the checklist certified to ensure that only qualified drivers/operators are issued permits or franchise.  At least once a month, reconcile records with the different sectors to determine registered active and inactive members, as against the records maintained in the Office of the Vice Mayor.  Maintain registry of all tricycle operators which includes the names and addresses, contact numbers and brands of tricycle, route, sector, body number together with an orderly file of supporting documents for reference and control;
assign personnel to conduct inspection of the tricycles to conform with the minimum standard of physical requirement/equipage;  


request the Chairman of the Committee on Transportation, and Peace, Order and Security to revisit the Resolution/Ordinances issued for effective regulation of operation of tricycles and implementation of the traffic rules and regulations;
conduct meeting with the PNP, barangays and different sectors (TODA) to enforce rules and regulations and resolve issues and concerns; and

take into consideration the hiring/assigning of additional task force personnel to enforce the traffic rules and regulations, and install CCTV for monitoring and recording purposes as one way to control colorum vehicles as well as promoting public safety and order.

We recommended that management:

Comply strictly with the procedures, guidelines and documentary requirements provided in Executive Order No. 1035 and Section 13.1 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 for the acquisition of private real properties or rights for infrastructure and other government development projects;
Submit an explanation for not subjecting the appraised values arrived at to prior review and approval of the Provincial Committee on Appraisal and provide the Audit Team with the basis for the valuation made per land classification, which was used for purposes of determining the selling prices of the two lots;
Make follow-up with the DENR/EMB for the immediate release of the Environmental Clearance Certificate (ECC) to facilitate the construction of housing at the Kainomayan Village; and
Follow up with the RD the immediate transfer of the certificate of title in favor of the Municipal Government to warrant the LGU’s absolute ownership.
